{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13082"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13082"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.03,0.01,0.04,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112292"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94341"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1929"},{"type":"tags","id":"2468"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14622"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45690"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112292"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her mother, who is concerned about her daughter\u0027s developmental milestones. The girl started sitting without support at one year, crawling at 18 months, and walking at two and a half years of age. Her mother reports the child currently has trouble tying her shoelaces, climbing stairs, and riding a bike. She has difficulty staying focused on tasks at school.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe girl was born at 34 weeks via caesarean section, weighing 1.2 kg. The pregnancy was uncomplicated. Her mother discloses that she consumed alcohol during the pregnancy and intermittently used folate supplements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has a smooth philtrum and thin upper lip. Her palpebral fissures appear short. Her height is 99cm (\u003C2nd centile), weight is 16.5kg (\u003C2nd centile), and BMI is 16.3 kg/m2 (z-score 0.58). Her occipitofrontal head circumference is below the 3rd percentile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA neurodevelopmental assessment reveals severe impairment in motor skills, memory, affect regulation, and adaptive behaviour. There is some impairment in cognition, language, attention, and executive function including impulse control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely additional finding on further examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiac murmur","Hepatomegaly","Lymphadenopathy","Joint hypermobility","Sensorineural hearing loss"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of foetal alcohol spectrum disorder, including characteristic facial features (smooth philtrum, thin upper lip, short palpebral fissures), growth restriction, microcephaly, and significant neurodevelopmental impairments. Children with foetal alcohol spectrum disorder have a high incidence of congenital heart defects, with studies showing cardiac abnormalities in 50-85% of affected individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecardiac murmur\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely additional finding on examination. Congenital heart defects associated with foetal alcohol spectrum disorder include ventricular septal defects, atrial septal defects, tetralogy of Fallot, and other structural abnormalities. These defects often present with audible murmurs on cardiac examination and may require echocardiographic evaluation for definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatomegaly\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with foetal alcohol spectrum disorder. While liver abnormalities can occur with prenatal alcohol exposure, hepatomegaly is not a characteristic finding in the established syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of foetal alcohol spectrum disorder. Generalised lymphadenopathy would suggest other conditions such as infection, malignancy, or immunodeficiency syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJoint hypermobility\u003C/strong\u003E may occur in some children with developmental disorders but is not specifically associated with foetal alcohol spectrum disorder. It is more characteristic of connective tissue disorders such as Ehlers-Danlos syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensorineural hearing loss\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in children with foetal alcohol spectrum disorder but is less common than cardiac defects. While hearing assessment is important in these children, cardiac abnormalities are more frequently encountered and would be the most likely additional finding on physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Foetal alcohol spectrum disorder is associated with a high incidence of congenital heart defects, particularly septal defects.","Cardiac murmurs are commonly found on examination in children with foetal alcohol spectrum disorder due to underlying structural heart disease.","Children with foetal alcohol spectrum disorder require comprehensive cardiac evaluation including echocardiography."],"references":["Wozniak JR, Riley EP, Charness ME. Clinical presentation, diagnosis, and management of fetal alcohol spectrum disorder. Lancet Neurol. 2019 Aug;18(8):760-770. doi: 10.1016/S1474-4422(19)30150-4. Epub 2019 May 31. PMID: 31160204; PMCID: PMC6995665."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94341"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13082"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94341"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-28T13:09:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-28T13:11:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5519"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112292"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating 